ax-accounting/tax-accounting-in-the-us/what-is-sales-tax.html">Sales Taxes</a>, etc.</p></div></div></div></section><section t4-group="Block" t4-bid="core_element_layout_2-columns" t4-type="default" id="iea1eh" class="t4b-section"><div data-highlightable="1" class="container"><div type="t4.row" id="ipj5zz" class="row"><div id="ip9dn6" class="cell col-12 col-lg-12"><img src="../../images/icon/eightprogresses/Progress-2.png" id="i71c2r" alt="Progress 2" width="183" height="183" loading="lazy"><h2 id="iufvil">A summary of U.S. corporate annual filing </h2><p id="ip5nat">Every year, U.S. companies are required to prepare and submit various reports to fulfill their legal obligations: </p></div><div id="iz7x07" class="cell col-lg-6 col-12"><div id="iphmbf" class="t4b-box d-flex"><div id="iwgyjs" class="t4b-box align-self-center"><div id="iw1zqt">1 </div></div><div id="i0osuh" class="t4b-box"><p id="ivht8j">Annual Report </p><p id="i0gx0v">This report is submitted to the State government where the company is incorporated, and includes updated information such as the company&#039;s address and the list of owners. It must be submitted annually alongside income tax declarations. </p></div></div></div><div id="ie6lyt" class="cell col-lg-6 col-12"><div id="ixl7zh" class="t4b-box d-flex"><div id="ibx7gw" class="t4b-box align-self-center"><div id="iz07yj">2 </div></div><div id="ibwzhj" class="t4b-box align-self-center"><p id="ialehb">Federal Income Tax Returns </p><p id="iizmif">U.S. companies need to file corporate income tax returns or partnership or personal income tax returns with the Federal government. The specific requirements and forms will vary based on the company type (LLC, Corporation, or S-Corporation) and the number of members/shareholders. </p></div></div></div><div id="ixpyyl" class="cell col-lg-6 col-12"><div id="i8ij0i" class="t4b-box d-flex"><div id="iw1yms" class="t4b-box align-self-center"><div id="iu3et3">3 </div></div><div id="ifr7zc" class="t4b-box"><p id=